article.description: Tim Duncan scored 23 points, including the last six points in overtime, and had 12 rebounds as the San Antonio Spurs beat the Memphis Grizzlies 99-93 on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Duncan's big OT effort lifts Spurs
article.linkText: Spurs barely beat Grizzlies for 17th straight time
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The San Antonio Spurs didn't care about earning any style points in beating the Memphis Grizzlies. Tim Duncan scored 23 points, including the last six points in overtime, and had 12 rebounds as the Spurs got a hard-fought 99-93 victory on Tuesday night. "Sometimes you just have to say, 'Thank you,"' San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich said. "We were just lucky tonight. Memphis did a great job of executing. All I can say is a win is a win, and I'm not giving it back." Antonio Daniels added 19 points, David Robinson added 14 points and 14 rebounds for the Spurs, who have defeated the Grizzlies 17 straight times. Pau Gasol and Shane Battier each scored 26 points for Memphis, which has lost four of its last five. "There's not much to say about this one other than it was a great game," Memphis coach Sidney Lowe said. "It was a great one to watch. Both teams played hard. I thought we showed a lot of guts and played with a lot of pride tonight. I told our guys to walk out of here with their heads held high tonight because they gave a great effort against a great team this evening." The teams went into overtime tied 87-87, and Duncan's bank shot with 36.3 seconds remaining gave the Spurs a 95-93 lead. Lorenzen Wright missed a shot for Memphis, and Duncan made two free throws with 26.4 seconds left to make it 97-93. Terry Porter closed the scoring with two free throws with 16.9 seconds remaining. "We don't feel fortunate at all," said Duncan, who shot 6-of-14 from the field. "We won the game fair and square. It was a hard-fought battle from the start until the end, and we played hard until the end. There are no moral victories anymore. A win is a win." In the fourth quarter, San Antonio went on an 8-0 run, led by consecutive 3-pointers by Daniels and Danny Ferry, to break a tie and take an 85-79 lead with 6:50 left. Duncan made two free throws to make it 87-79, but Memphis rallied to cut the lead to 87-85 on consecutive baskets by Wright, the last a dunk shot with 2:26 remaining. After missing on three straight possessions, Memphis tied it at 87 on Battier's 15-foot jumper with 24.5 seconds remaining. Robinson misfired on a jump shot from the free-throw line as time expired in regulation, sending the game to overtime. San Antonio went scoreless over the final 6:20 of regulation. "We had a lot of opportunities," said Robinson, who also blocked three shots. "When things kind of break down and you lose your rhythm a little bit, it's nice to know that you can grind it out. We got to get wins like this. There's been a couple that we've lost like this, so this is a good one." After trailing by as many as 15 points in the third quarter, Memphis went on a 28-11 run to lead 71-69 on two free throws by Gasol with 24.1 seconds to play in the period. Daniels' running jump shot tied it at 71-all heading to the final quarter. San Antonio outscored Memphis 27-16 in the second quarter and led 54-41 at halftime as Robinson and Steve Smith each had 13 first-half points. Gasol had 16 first-half points for the Grizzlies. "We were going out to play and trying to work hard," Gasol said. "They played well. They did what they were supposed to do. Next time we'll beat them."

Game notes
Grizzlies point guard Jason Williams, who was held to five points in the first half, did not play in the second half after reaggravating a right big toe injury. ... With the win, San Antonio improved to 22-3 all-time against the Memphis/Vancouver franchise. ... The Spurs are 2-0 this season against Memphis, with a 83-79 win on Dec. 30 in Tennessee. ... Duncan had his 43rd double-double of the season and 263rd of his career. ... The Spurs have held 38 of the last 42 opponents under 100 points. ... Memphis is 6-22 on the road this season.
